The Vice President of the United States, Mike Pence, met with the Taoiseach of Ireland, Leo Varadkar, in Dublin. They discussed the strong relationship between the US and Ireland, as well as the trade and investment ties between the two countries. The leaders also talked about the current status of Brexit negotiations and its potential impact on the border between Ireland and Northern Ireland. Pence encouraged the European Union and the United Kingdom to work together to find a solution that maintains the free flow of goods across the border. They also discussed the economic opportunities of a future US-EU free trade agreement and agreed to work towards it. Pence praised Ireland's cooperation with the US and NATO partners on cyber security and counter-terrorism, and urged them to consider the risks posed by untrustworthy vendors in the development of 5G infrastructure. They agreed to work together on this issue.